  <mads:note type="source">"Under the lemma Ἀρχίου, the Anthologia Palatina records 37 epigrams (disputed are Anth. Pal. 
  5,98; 6,194; 7,165; 9,27; 64; 357; 16,154); sometimes the name is more closely defined as γραμματικοῦ (6,194), 
  Μακεδόνος (7,140), Βυζαντίου (7,278), Μυτιληναίου (7,696; 9,19; 111; 339), and νεωτέρου (9,91; 10,10): 
  five different poets, all of whom otherwise unknown. All attempts to attribute the material -- 
  predominantly pedantic imitations, especially of Leonidas and of Antipater of Sidon -- to any individual poet
  within this group, have met with failure. It seems very likely that some of these poems were written by 
  Licinius Archias of Antioch, Cicero's famous contemporary (cf. SH 194-199)." in Degani, Enzo (Bologna).
  "Archias." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and Helmuth Schneider
  . Brill, 2007. Brill Online. Tufts University Library. 19 July 2007</mads:note>
